    description: "Run a cron on the 5th of every month with 0 0 5 * *.",
    explanation: "The cron expression 0 0 5 * * runs at 00:00 on the 5th of every month. The day-of-month field (5) specifies which calendar days to trigger. This produces 1 execution per month. Monthly schedules are commonly used for billing cycle tasks, subscription renewals, monthly report generation, account statement creation, database archiving, compliance audits, payroll processing, and infrastructure cost reporting. For Quartz Scheduler, use 0 0 5 * ? (swap day-of-month and day-of-week fields, use ? for day-of-week). For AWS EventBridge, use cron(0 0 5 * ? *) (add year field, use ? for day-of-week). For Kubernetes CronJob, use schedule: \"0 0 5 * *\" directly. Note: months with fewer days than the specified day-of-month will skip that month. For example, day 31 runs only in months with 31 days (7 months out of 12). For the last day of every month, use 0 0 28-31 * * with a script that checks if tomorrow is the 1st. Cron does not natively support \"last business day\" or \"Nth weekday of the month\" logic. Implement these rules in your script using date utilities.",
